{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487352"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:07:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:07:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"328"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/328"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.47,0.05,0.01,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"328"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41890"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/328"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"328"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26862"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4256"},{"type":"tags","id":"4272"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"10769"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10770"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42060"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41890"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 36-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department of the local rural hospital with pain in both knees. His symptoms came on about 12 hours after he had spent the morning laying a concrete floor, much of which meant kneeling in the wet mix. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. The photograph shows the appearance of his knees (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Admit for wound debridement","Transfer to regional burns unit","Admit for bed rest and antibiotics","Admit for bed rest and leg elevation","Saline-soaked dressings and review next day"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhilst most mild burns cases can probably be managed in a rural centre, there are certain types of burns and areas of the body that burns affect that demand specialist attention. One of these is a burn that affects a joint (such as this case) and one where there has been a chemical burn, which often means that the injury will be full thickness. If not evident on presentation, such a type of injury should be treated as a full thickness burn until proven otherwise. Chemical burns can be insidious in onset and become deep second or third degree burns in late stages. Chemical burns account for about 30% of burn-associated deaths and thus need immediate and specialised treatment. Cement is an alkaline material - calcium oxide when dry, changing to calcium hydroxide when wet. Whilst dry, the material is relatively safe, but once wet, it absorbs water and if allowed to stay on the skin, the alkaline material will be absorbed, damaging the underlying skin. This patient has several reasons that merit prompt \u003Cstrong\u003Etransfer to a burns unit\u003C/strong\u003E and these include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESevere chemical burns\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBurns affecting a critical area (major joints)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFull thickness burns exceeding more than 5% of the total body surface area\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdmission with bed rest\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate in this case and \u003Cstrong\u003Ewound debridement\u003C/strong\u003E would likely need to take place in a tertiary centre that can also accommodate skin grafting and advanced wound care. In the immediate management the patient should be assessed via primary survey, copious irrigation and regular wound assessment. Intravenous fluids could also be started, based on burns protocol. He may require \u003Cstrong\u003Eantibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Esaline-soaked dressings\u003C/strong\u003E as part of his overall management, but they are not part of his immediate management plan, which must focus on transfer to a burns unit.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Burns involving joints must be managed in a burns unit."],"references":["Neiraja G, Perera M, Sawhney R, Perera E. Cutaneous chemical burns: assessment and early management. Aust J Gen Pract. 2015;44:135-9. Available at:\u00a0https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2015/march/cutaneous-chemical-burns-assessment-and-early-management/.","Ng N, Abdullah A, Milner S. Cement Burn. Eplasty Journal. 2015;15. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4347359/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26862"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"328"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"10493"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"10493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/10493"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/86cb3a4b-7192-4a57-9dfa-8fd8ece8a083.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/86cb3a4b-7192-4a57-9dfa-8fd8ece8a083.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":